{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504799"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2373"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2373"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.06,0.04,0.39,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106307"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2373"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88775"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"2101"},{"type":"tags","id":"6041"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2342"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38487"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106307"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with pain in her right hip after a fall. She was unable to get up off the floor, and her husband called an ambulance. She is normally in good health, and the only medication she takes is alendronate, together with calcium supplements. On examination, she appears distressed with pain. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The right leg appears shortened and externally rotated. There is marked tenderness over the right hip, and movement is severely limited due to pain. X-rays of the right hip and femur are performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subcapital femoral fracture","Transcervical femoral fracture","Basicervical femoral fracture","Reverse oblique intertrochanteric fracture","Isolated greater trochanteric fracture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and X-ray findings are consistent with a hip fracture in an elderly patient following a fall. The external rotation and shortening of the leg are classic signs of a displaced hip fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReverse oblique intertrochanteric fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis. This is a subtype of intertrochanteric fracture where the fracture line runs from the lesser trochanter obliquely upward and laterally (in contrast to the typical intertrochanteric fracture pattern). These fractures are inherently unstable because the fracture line is oriented in a direction that allows the proximal fragment to displace medially and the distal fragment to displace laterally under the pull of the adductor muscles. This creates a tendency for the fracture to collapse into varus. Treatment typically involves a long cephalomedullary nail rather than a sliding hip screw to provide adequate stability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcapital femoral fracture\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a fracture at the junction of the femoral head and neck. This type of fracture is intracapsular and would appear higher on the X-ray, closer to the femoral head. Subcapital fractures have different management considerations due to the risk of avascular necrosis of the femoral head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranscervical femoral fracture\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through the middle portion of the femoral neck. This is also an intracapsular fracture and would be seen in the mid-neck region of the femur on the X-ray, not in the intertrochanteric region as shown here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasicervical femoral fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is located at the base of the femoral neck, at the junction with the intertrochanteric region. While closer to the area of this patient\u0027s fracture, a basicervical fracture would not have the reverse oblique pattern extending below the lesser trochanter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsolated greater trochanteric fracture\u003C/strong\u003E involves only the greater trochanter without extension into the intertrochanteric region. These fractures are typically stable and may be managed non-operatively in some cases. The imaging in this case shows a more extensive fracture pattern involving the intertrochanteric region with subtrochanteric extension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Reverse oblique fractures are unstable intertrochanteric fractures with a fracture line that extends from the lesser trochanter to the lateral cortex.","Reverse oblique fractures are biomechanically unstable and tend to collapse into varus deformity if not properly stabilized.","Long cephalomedullary nails are the preferred fixation method for reverse oblique fractures due to their biomechanical advantages over plate fixation."],"references":["Bhandari M, Swiontkowski M. Management of Acute Hip Fracture. N Engl J Med. 2017 Nov 23;377(21):2053-2062. doi: 10.1056/NEJMcp1611090. PMID: 29166235. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29166235/","Callaghan JJ, Liu SS, Haidukewych GJ. Subcapital fractures: a changing paradigm. J Bone Joint Surg Br. 2012 Nov;94(11 Suppl A):19-21. doi: 10.1302/0301-620X.94B11.30617. PMID: 23118374. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23118374/","Medda S, Reeves RA, Pilson H. Subtrochanteric Femur Fractures. 2023 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29939580. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29939580/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88775"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2373"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20043"},{"type":"media","id":"20044"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20043"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/54359964-be2e-45b1-9a6f-dd35913ccca6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/54359964-be2e-45b1-9a6f-dd35913ccca6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1260,"height":1040}},{"type":"media","id":"20044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20044"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8c7c1993-9ae6-4c9b-b511-ece3deddb412.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8c7c1993-9ae6-4c9b-b511-ece3deddb412.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1040,"height":1380}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88775"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T21:10:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T10:27:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2373"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106307"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda